    "analysis": "We have followed the workflow: global thresholds (P50/P95) were computed from full series, the incident window (2021-03-24 16:30–17:00 UTC+8) was scanned, anomalies were detected and then filtered to 'severe' groups (in-window max > P95 by >50%). Results so far: (1) MG02 and MG01 have the largest counts of severe metric KPI groups (30 and 28 respectively) with notable disk IO and CPU WIO breaches (earliest MG01 severe metric anomalies around 16:31; some MG02 disk spikes at 16:30–16:34). (2) Trace analysis shows very large latency spikes involving dockerA2 (trace.self.duration_p95 severity ≈ 59x at 16:30) and multiple MG01/MG02↔dockerA* trace durations with severity commonly >3x–4x at 16:31. According to the localization rules, when multiple service/container-level components are faulty, we should use traces to select the most downstream faulty component in the call chain. The trace results indicate dockerA2 exhibited the single largest relative spike and its earliest severe trace timestamp (16:30) precedes many MG metric anomalies (16:31). To confirm the root cause component and reason, we must check resource metrics of the most downstream trace-faulty containers (dockerA2, dockerA1) to see which resource exceeded thresholds (CPU, memory, disk I/O, network) at the earliest severe timestamp. This will distinguish whether the root cause is a container-level processing slowdown (e.g., CPU or JVM) or node-level resource contention (e.g., disk IO on MG nodes) that then propagated.",
